 {"id":"franken_networkx-dagtopo1","title":"CONFORMANCE: DAG topology enumeration oracle setup","description":"First sub-bead for franken_networkx-dagtopo: add a NetworkX-vs-FrankenNetworkX DAG topology matrix and close the order/exception divergences it exposes for all_topological_sorts, antichains, transitive_reduction, dag_longest_path, and dag_longest_path_length.","status":"in_progress","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-04-24T18:19:26Z","created_by":"cod-franken_networkx","updated_at":"2026-04-24T18:19:26Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
 {"id": "franken_networkx-ssintfloat", "title": "REVIEW: [MEDIUM] single_source_dijkstra / bellman_ford distances returned float for all-int weights", "description": "nx's weighted shortest-path dicts preserve integer distances when every edge weight is int; fnx's Rust _raw_single_source_dijkstra and _raw_single_source_bellman_ford_path_length coerced distances to float regardless of input types. So with weights {2, 1} fnx returned {0: 0.0, 1: 2.0, 2: 3.0} while nx returned {0: 0, 1: 2, 2: 3}. Since 2 == 2.0 in Python most equality tests pass, but isinstance(dist, int) checks and downstream code that expects int type silently diverged. Added _sp_edge_weights_all_int probe + _sp_coerce_dist_to_int helper. When all edge weights are int, coerce integer-valued floats back to int in single_source_dijkstra and single_source_bellman_ford_path_length. Float inputs stay float.", "status": "closed", "priority": 3, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T22:30:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T22:30:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T22:30:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Int-preserving coercion on all-int-weight inputs", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
 {"id": "franken_networkx-reverseinstance", "title": "REVIEW: [MEDIUM] DiGraph.reverse(copy=False) returns non-DiGraph-subclass view", "description": "nx's DiGraph.reverse(copy=False) returns a DiGraph-subclass view that passes ``isinstance(r, nx.DiGraph) == True``. fnx's reverse-view class (``_ReverseDirectedView``) is not a subclass of fnx.DiGraph and fnx.DiGraph is a Rust class that doesn't support ABC virtual registration, so isinstance(r, fnx.DiGraph) returns False. Users passing the reverse view to functions that do isinstance checks would fail. Queued for deeper fix \u2014 the view class needs to be reworked to inherit from fnx.DiGraph or at least pass the isinstance check. Both libraries' views are LIVE (reflect mutations on the parent), so only the isinstance check diverges.", "status": "open", "priority": 3, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T22:30:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T22:30:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
+{"id": "franken_networkx-triadsempty", "title": "REVIEW: [MEDIUM] triads_by_type included empty buckets for every triad type; nx only lists non-empty", "description": "nx.triads_by_type returns a sparse dict keyed only by triad types that actually appear in the graph. fnx's implementation pre-populated all 16 triad types (003, 012, 021C, 021D, 021U, 030C, 030T, 102, 111D, 111U, 120C, 120D, 120U, 201, 210, 300) with empty lists and returned them all. Callers iterating items / checking membership saw 16 keys on fnx vs 4 on nx for simple graphs \u2014 causing off-by-one in downstream loops and ``'300' in triads`` returning True on fnx even when the graph had no 300-type triads. Drop empty buckets before returning to match nx's sparse contract.", "status": "closed", "priority": 3, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T23:00:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T23:00:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T23:00:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Filter empty buckets", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
